Smart enumerations, also known as value objects, are a fundamental concept in Domain-Driven Design (DDD). They are used to represent a set of named values that have a specific meaning within the domain.

**Example: Color Enumeration**

Let's consider a simple example of a color enumeration in a DDD C# application.

```csharp
public sealed class Color
{
    public static readonly Color Red = new Color("Red");
    public static readonly Color Green = new Color("Green");
    public static readonly Color Blue = new Color("Blue");

    private readonly string _name;

    private Color(string name)
    {
        _name = name;
    }

    public string Name => _name;

    public override string ToString() => _name;

    public static implicit operator string(Color color) => color.Name;

    public static Color FromName(string name)
    {
        switch (name)
        {
            case "Red":
                return Red;
            case "Green":
                return Green;
            case "Blue":
                return Blue;
            default:
                throw new ArgumentException($"Invalid color name: {name}", nameof(name));
        }
    }
}
